earch in Darwin's manuscripts and at the Beagle's remotest ports of call, Sponsel takes us from the ocean to the Origin and beyond. He provides a vivid new picture of Darwin's career as a voyaging naturalist and metropolitan author, and in doing so makes a bold argument about how we should understand the history of scientific theories.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aGeologyzGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 4aAlexander von Humboldt. 4aCharles Darwin. 4aCharles Lyell. 4aOn the Origin of Species. 4aSociology of Scientific Knowledge. 4aauthorship. 4abiography. 4acoral reefs. 4aevolution. 4ageology. 4atheories. 4atheory. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226523255423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226523255.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles